questionTemplates.text:
Man: Have you seen my old shoes? I thought they were under the chair by the television.
Woman: Not any more! They're by the door with the other rubbish. I've been tidying the flat.
{a}

W: What's the noise?
M: That's the boys playing football.
{a}

M: Today's the last day that Harry Potter is on. We planned to go and see it after school.
W: I'd love to, but Professor Brian wants to speak with me.
{a}

F: What was the party like last night, Jim?
M: Not too bad.
{a}

F: How far is your school?
M: It's about 15 minutes bus ride.
{a}

M: I left 20 pages here to copy. Here is the receipt.
W: I'm sorry, sir. But we're a little behind. Could you come back in a few minutes?
{a}

W: Did you visit the Television Tower when you had your vacation in Shanghai last summer?
M: I couldn't make it last June. But I finally visited it twomonths later. I plan to visit it again sometime next year.
{a}

M: I'll meet you at six, OK?
F: Could you make it later? I'll have to make a call at that time.
{a}

F: Can I help you?
M: Yes, I want to buy a stamp for the letter.
{a}

F: Excuse me, do you know how to use this machine?
M: Um... well... sorry... but I think you may ask the managerhere.
{a}

M: Where is the closest telephone, Mary?
W: Why not use mine, Tom? I won't ask you to pay.
{a}

M: I forgot all about the two o'clock meeting. Tom's going to kill me.
W: Oh, God! I can see why you are upset. You can really be annoying when something important slips in your mind.
{a}

W: This coffee never seems quite right to me.
M: Why don't you try some tea?
{a}

W: After the way it is being used, the photocopier is not going to make it through the rest of the year.
M: The year! It's supposed to be good for four!
{a}

W: I just can't believe this is our last year. College is going by fast.
M: Yeah. We'll have to face the real world soon. So, have you figured out what you're going to do after you graduate? I just can't believe this is our last year.
{a}

M: Alice, I want to buy you a watch. Which one do you like?
F: I like the red one, Dad.
{a}

F: Could you tell me something about the city?
M: Certainly. I am almost sixty now, and I lived here all my life. I know it very well.
{a}

M: I'm really exhausted, but I don't want to miss the film that comes on at 11.
W: If I were you, I'd skip it. We both have to get up early tomorrow, and anyway, I've heard it isn't that exciting.
{a}

M: Can you possibly lend me $10 until payday?
W: It's out of the question.
{a}

W: These days have been so hot. Shall we go swimming at school this weekend?
M: I'd love to, but yesterday I promised my friends to go fishing with them.
{a}

M: I can't go to the zoo with you tomorrow, because I have got a cold.
W: I'm sorry to hear that.
{a}

F: This dress is much better, and the color is good.
M: You are fight, madam, the blue dress is better than the green one.
{a}

M: Can you tell me how to telephone other rooms?
W: You just dial 0 and then the room number. It's very simple.
{a}

M: Hello, may I speak to Henry, please?
F: Hold on. Henry, your phone call.
{a}

W: I thought it was a great movie â€“ so visually exciting and sharks look really scary at times.
M: I hated to admit it, but it made me jump a bit of times too. I guess recent advances in camera technology helped.
{a}
